  "updated_summary": "In a modern office, a man in a light blue checkered shirt and glasses, seated at a round wooden table, initiates a video call, discussing the 'issues we're going to have to unpack' and the 'fourth industrial revolution,' while a phone rings. He introduces Dr. Libby Sander, a 'Future of Work expert' from Bond University, and Vaibhav Namburi, a 'Technology and Artificial Intelligence expert,' both appearing from home settings. Dr. Sander explains the significant evolution of work over the past century, noting reduced working hours, flexible arrangements, and the four-day work week, attributing a 'huge shift' to technology which has made jobs 'easier to do' and provided 'more leisure time.' Vaibhav Namburi elaborates on automation, predicting the phasing out of mundane jobs over the next 10-30 years, leading to retraining for 'upward level skills' like people management and creative work, allowing humans to focus on cognitive and creative aspects. The moderator questions if this century will finally allow people to work less, referencing past promises of leisure time versus longer hours. Vaibhav agrees it's a 'great question,' predicting more automation will free up time and posing whether people will use it for opportunities or leisure, seeking work-life balance. Dr. Sander responds to Vaibhav, agreeing automation is essential due to a declining workforce and emphasizing the need for reskilling as jobs are impacted. She concludes by predicting that in the next 40 years, people would be working shorter working weeks, driven by a desire for purpose-driven work, more family time, and interests outside of work, contrasting with pre-pandemic norms."
